Japanese Egg Sando

Yield: ~5–6 sandwiches
Target texture: smooth, lightly sweet, rich but clean

⸻

Ingredients
	•	10 large eggs
	•	Japanese mayonnaise (Kewpie): 7 1/2 tbsp (110–115 g)
	•	Sugar: 1 1/4 tsp (5 g)
	•	Fine salt: 5/8 tsp (3.5 g)
	•	White pepper: 4–5 light pinches
	•	Milk bread (shokupan): 10–12 slices
	•	Unsalted butter, soft: ~60–70 g total (5–7 g per slice)

Optional (choose ONE only):
	•	1 1/4 tsp milk (softer mouthfeel)
	•	1/2 tsp rice vinegar (brighter finish)
	•	+1 extra yolk (luxury café style)

⸻

Method
	1.	Boil eggs
Lower eggs into boiling water; cook 10 minutes. Ice bath immediately. Peel.
	2.	Dry
Let peeled eggs air-dry 5 minutes to prevent dilution.
	3.	Separate & process
	•	Remove yolks; grate or press through a fine sieve until powdery-smooth.
	•	Finely knife-mince whites (very small, even pieces).
	4.	Season yolks
Mix yolks with mayo, sugar, salt, and white pepper until glossy and silky. Add optional milk/vinegar/yolk if using.
	5.	Fold
Gently fold whites into the yolk base. Do not mash.
	6.	Bread prep
Butter each slice edge-to-edge (5–7 g). Trim crusts if desired.
	7.	Assemble
Spread filling generously to a compressed thickness of ~1.5 cm (5/8 in). Close sandwiches.
	8.	Set & slice
Wrap tightly; chill 15–20 minutes. Slice cleanly with a sharp knife.